vectorData.altText: 2. The _______________ nerve is associated with cutaneous sensation over the lateral aspect of the forearm, as indicated by the letter A.
That's right!  The musculocutaneous nerve ends as lateral cutaneous nerve of the forearm, monitoring skin of the lateral forearm.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The musculocutaneous nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm, notably, the biceps brachii and the brachialis. Do you remember their actions?
Recall that the musculocutaneous nerve ends as the lateral cutaneous nerve of the forearm, which monitors the skin of the lateral forearm.
Therefore, a lesion of the musculocutaneous nerve can cause sensory signs (pain, dysesthesia) in the lateral aspect of the forearm.

brachialis: flexion of the elbow
biceps brachii: flexion of the elbow and supination of the forearm
